Up for sale is a used but in grat condition Ar15 with three 30 round Pmags and a well equipped range bag. The COMPLETED upper with BCM bolt carrier group was purchased from BCM. I did not assemble this upper myself. The upper consists of a BCM forged upper, Midwest industries 12" Super light weight keymod rail, BCM 16" pencil profile barrel chambered in 5.56 w/ 1 in 7 twist rate with the standard A2 birdcage flash hider. The barrel has approximately 3500-4000 rounds through it and is still very accurate. At 100 yards on a bench with the aimpoint pro using 60gr amax projectiles, 23gr of H335 powder, we were averaging 2 inch to 4 inch groups. The rifle definitely performs better then we were capable of shooting with the red dot at 100 yards, though I never used any magnification on the rifle, so its true accuracy is not known to me. Based on my use of the rifle, with proper benching and magnification you could get 1inch groups with ease and even smaller gorups with practice. This rifle is amazingly light and a great above average entry level rifle for anyone looking to get into the AR 15 world or even for 3 gun competitions.

The lower receiver is a Spikes Tactical Pirate lower with a standard mil spec parts kit installed. It has a Magpul CTR stock and a BCM Mod 0 grip with rubberized bottom compartment for storage.

The aimpoint Pro is a 2moa dot and comes with the ratchet locking mount and is in perfect working condition. Has been running for approximately 6 months out of its 3 year battery life. The battery is cheap to replace with a 3 year lifespan.

title: For Sale:  RARE: GSG-552 SD + 1,500rds .22LR
postcontent:
Through sheer chance I lucked in to picking up the very hard to find GSG-552 SD recently.  It's brand new and has never been fired.  The GSG-552 SD was a clone of the H&K MP5 SD and after some legal action they were no longer able to manufacture these awesome weapons.  It's a suppressor shroud, not the real thing, and I'll just give my first impressions here:

First and foremost, this weapon does not feel cheap and plastic like a lot of tactical .22LRs do.  It's robust and heavy and gives the impression that it's one well built firearm.  Second, it's a step away from the AR15 style rifles, so while everyone and their brother has one, this will definitely stand out of a crowd.  I couldn't get it out of the store I found it without every single person at the counter inquiring about it.

It comes with the original factory box, 3 22rd mags, the multi-tool, all of the original literature/stickers/extra sights/etc, and a lock.  What I'm also going to do is toss in just over 1,500rds of .22LR ammunition of varying makes.  It's almost impossible to find .22LR now a days and what good is a rifle with no ammo, especially if it becomes a Christmas present!

I'm asking $700 and please, no low ball offers, this weapon is no longer being manufactured and is incredibly rare to find. I will require a bill of sale be made out, which I will provide, and a valid Florida driver's license. Also, I can only do a local pick up as I have two small children and I work quite a lot, but I'll work with the buyer as much as possible to make the deal go smoothly.

title: For Trade:  Goex 2F and 3F Black Powder in Cans
postcontent:
I have 2 cans of black powder that have been open, but I have carefully weighed and examined the remaining contents as well as the containers to make sure they haven't been contaminated, previously mixed or otherwise damaged.

The can of 3F contains 11.4 ounces.  The can is in good shape and doesn't have rust damage to the paint or exposed metal except a few blackened tiny blackened spots on the bottom of the can.  This can is 71% full,  The price is $12.   If you need a little less than a pound to go hunting or to shoot some tin cans off the fence, this deal is for you.  

The can of 2F contains 15.7 ounces.  The can is in even better condition and doesn't have anything written in Sharpie on it.  The can is still shiny and would be practical for regular use, then the empty can could be used for decoration in the man cave.  This can is $17.

Both cans, in the process of having their contents weighed, were poured out as completely as practical.  There were no clumps, oddly colored particles and the grain size within each can was uniform (all of the 3F's were about the same size and all of the 2F's were about the same size). Neither can's contents smelled sour or "off".

The amounts quoted in the ad are the current contents of each can.  I initially removed 0.1 oz from each can in order to verify that the powder ignites properly. They were tested individually and both tests were successful.

Please drop me a note if you are ready to execute a deal.  I have as much desire to see another shooter enjoying this stuff as the lucky buyer will be to get it and get shooting.  I know this stuff was scarce a couple of years ago.  Why not buy these to shoot and keep a few of those sealed cans on the shelf?
